stian saint of this name, who is supposed to have lived in the 6th century, but about whom nothing is known except for a largely fictional life dating from half a millennium later, was popular throughout Europe in the early Middle Ages and was regarded as the patron of peasants and horses. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Italian   Leonardo  , Polish, Slovenian, etc.   Lenart   or   Lenard  , and probably also their derivatives. Compare   Larned  ,   Learned  , and   Yenor  .","Irish (Fermanagh): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Fhionáin</b> or of   Langan  .","German: variant of   Leonhard  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Charles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic word, <i>karl</i>, meaning ‘free man’, akin to Old English <i>ceorl</i> ‘man’. The name, Latin form <i>Carolus</i>, owed its popularity in medieval Europe to the Frankish leader  Charlemagne  (  ?742–814 ), who in  800  established himself as Holy Roman Emperor. His name (Latin <i>Carolus Magnus</i>) means ‘Charles the Great’. <i>Carolus</i>—or <i>Karl</i>, the German form—was a common name among Frankish leaders, including Charlemagne's grandfather  Charles Martel  (  688–741 ). <i>Charles</i> is the French form. The name occurs occasionally in medieval Britain as <i>Karolus</i> or <i>Carolus</i>; it had a certain vogue in West Yorkshire from the 1400s, particularly among gentry families. The form <i>Charles</i> was chosen by  Mary Queen  of Scots (  1542–87 ), who had been brought up in France, for her son, <i>Charles James</i> (  1566–1625 ), who became  King James VI  of Scotland and, from  1603 ,  James I  of England. His son and grandson both reigned as  King Charles , and the name thus became established in the 17th century both in the Stuart royal house and among English and Scottish supporters of the Stuart monarchy. In the 18th century it was to some extent favoured, along with   James  , by Jacobites, supporters of the exiled Stuarts, opposed to the Hanoverian monarchy, especially in the Highlands of Scotland. In the 19th century the popularity of the name was further enhanced by romanticization of the story of ‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’, leader of the  1745  rebellion."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Charles Lennard I was born in 1341, in Soham with Barway, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of John Mychael Lennard and Mrs John Mychael Lennard. He had at least 2 sons with Lady Charlotte Lawrence. He died in Soham, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1341–":"1341–Surnud","1341–Male":"1341–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1370–1407":"1370–1407","1393–Male":"1393–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","before 1341":"enne 1341","1320":"1320","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","2 April 1393":"2. aprill 1393","1407":"1407","Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Clavering, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Soham, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Soham, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Pluckley, Kent, England":"Pluckley, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1341–":"1341–Kuollut","1341–Male":"1341–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1370–1407":"1370–1407","1393–Male":"1393–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","before 1341":"ennen vuotta 1341","1320":"1320","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1370":"1370","2 April 1393":"2. huhtikuuta 1393","1407":"1407","Clavering, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Clavering, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Soham, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Soham, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Pluckley, Kent, England":"Pluckley, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1341–":"1341–Décédé","1341–Male":"1341–Décédé","1350–Fema